canonical:
  title: 謝李春川送野猪頭
  author: 成俔
  language: lzh
  text: 將軍馬上神臂弓一發五羓誇豪雄磊磈載入明光宮饔官承命分臘紅自離鑾坡今卄載盂鉢凄涼困葅菜春川太守寄書札忽然覩此吾猳艾當初應作人立啼畢竟未免遭屠刲山中美味不獨享白茅純束來相携剛毛底虱相吊哭烟湯翠釜豊胹熟棘匕拘出香滿盤鸞刀紛紛如截玉多謝老饞今得飽半醉逍遙自捫腹
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 謝李春川送野猪頭
  author: 成俔
  language: lzh
  text: 將軍馬上神臂弓。一發五羓誇豪雄。磊磈載入明光宮。饔官承命分臘紅。自離鑾坡今卄載。盂鉢凄涼困葅菜。春川太守寄書札。忽然覩此吾猳艾。當初應作人立啼。畢竟未免遭屠刲。山中美味不獨享。白茅純束來相携。剛毛底虱相吊哭。烟湯翠釜豊胹熟。棘匕拘出香滿盤。鸞刀紛紛如截玉。多謝老饞今得飽。半醉逍遙自捫腹。
korean:
  title: 사 이춘천 송 야저두
  author: 성현
  language: kor
  text: |-
    장군이 말을 타고 귀신 같은 활솜씨로
    ‘한 발에 다섯 돼지’로 명수를 자랑하여
    듬뿍한 것을 명광궁에 실어 들어가면
    옹관이 어명을 받아 납일 고기를 나눠 주네
    내가 난파를 떠난 지 이십 년
    밥상에 처량하게도 나물ㆍ김치도 없더니
    춘천 태수가 편지를 보내 와서
    문득 이 멧돼지 새끼를 보게 됐네
    당초엔 필시 사람처럼 서서 웃었으리만
    필경 잡혀서 도살을 당했구나
    산중의 좋은 맛을 혼자 자시기 무엇하여
    ‘흰 띠[白茅]로 묶어’ 멀리 보내 왔네그려
    빳빳한 털, 돼지 이가 조상하며 울고
    가마에 삶아 내니 물씬ㆍ푸짐 잘 익었네
    작살 숟갈로 끌어 내니 소반에 가득한 향기
    난도로 점점이 저며 내니 옥인 듯
    고마워라, 늙은 게걸이가 이제야 배불러서
    얼근하여 건들건들 배를 쓸고 앉았네
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1410_010_0200&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 흰 띠[白茅]로 묶어 : '
    value: 백모돈속 유녀여옥(白茅純束有女如玉)에서 나온 말이다. 《詩經 召南》
english:
  title: A Poem of Thanks to Lee Chuncheon, the Governor, for Sending a Wild Boar's Head
  author: Seong Hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A general on horseback, with the bow-arm of a ghost,
    With one shot downs five boars, boasting mastery's utmost.
    The bounty heaped high enters the bright palace hall,
    The royal kitchen receives the command, distributes the winter meat to all.

    Twenty years have passed since I left the capital's shore,
    On my table sits only withered greens and pickled store.
    Then the Governor of Chuncheon sent a letter my way,
    And sudden before me appears a wild boar's young prey.

    Once it must have stood laughing like a man in the wood,
    Yet in the end it could not escape the butcher's blade as it should.
    Why keep the mountain's delicacy all for oneself alone?
    Wrapped in white reeds, it traveled far from its home.

    Coarse bristles and tusks seem to keen and lament,
    Yet steamed in the bronze kettle, tender and savory, well spent.
    The bone-spatula draws forth fragrant mounds on the plate,
    The jade-bright blade slices pieces—each piece wrought with fate.

    Thank you, old glutton that I am, now at last satisfied!
    Slightly drunk, I sit swaying, stroking my belly with pride.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase 'wrapped in white reeds' alludes to a line from the Book of Poetry (Shijing), suggesting careful, respectful presentation of a gift.
  - key: ''
    value: The references to the 'bright palace hall' and 'royal kitchen' evoke the speaker's former proximity to power and status, now lost.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Ghost-armed bow'' (神臂弓) is a legendary weapon of exceptional accuracy, emphasizing the hunter''s skill.'
